Question 1

scrape_url <- function(x) {
  urls <- x %>%
    read_html() %>%
    html_nodes(".inactive a") %>%
    html_attr("href") %>%
    paste("http://www.ratebeer.com", .,sep = "")
  
  for (i in 1:3) {
      check_url<- read_html(urls[i]) %>%
      html_nodes("#brewerTable a:nth-child(1)") %>% 
      html_text()
    
  if (length(check_url) == 0) {
    urls <- urls[-i]
  }
  }
  
  return(urls)
}

This function, which I named scrape_url, takes the state url as an input and outputs the meadery, cidery, and sake producer urls for that respective state. It does this by taking the meadery, cidery, and sake producer specific node (which is called â€œ.inactive aâ€) and combines it with â€œhttp://www.ratebeer.comâ€ in order to form three complete urls.

However, not all states have any producers listed on their meadery, cidery, or sake producer pages. Therefore, I used a for loop to look through each url and put any names of producers (using the â€œ#brewerTable a:nth-child(1)â€ node) into a vector called check_url. Then, I used an if statement to decide whether to keep the url based off whether the length of check_url was zero. If it was zero, this meant that there were no producers and the statement would therefore remove that url.

nc_urls <- scrape_url(nc_producers)
wy_urls <- scrape_url(wy_producers)

Question 2

scrape_beverage_producer <- function(x) {
  #1.a: Get name of beverage producer
  beverage_producer <- x %>%
    read_html() %>%
    html_nodes("#brewerTable a:nth-child(1)") %>% 
    html_text()

  #1.b: Get active producer city names
  active_cities <- x %>%
    read_html() %>%
    html_nodes(".filter") %>% 
    html_text()

  #1.b1: Get closed producer city names
  closed_cities <- x %>%
    read_html() %>%
    html_nodes("#brewerTable span") %>% 
    html_text()
  
  cities <- c(active_cities, closed_cities)
  
  #1.c: Get type of establishment
  types <- x %>%
    read_html() %>%
    html_nodes("td.hidden-xs.hidden-sm") %>% 
    html_text()
  
  #1.d: Get the beverage counts
  counts <- x %>%
    read_html() %>%
    html_nodes(".hidden-sm+ td") %>% 
    html_text() %>% 
    str_trim() %>% 
    as.numeric()
  
  #1.e: Get the year in which it was established
  ests <- x %>%
    read_html() %>%
    html_nodes("td:nth-child(5)") %>% 
    html_text() %>% 
    as.numeric()
  
  #1.f: Get the status (active or closed)
  status_active <- rep("Active", length(active_cities))
  
  status_closed <- rep("Closed", length(closed_cities))
  
  status <- c(status_active, status_closed)
  
  #Create the data frame
  state_beverage_producers <- tibble(
    name = beverage_producer,
    city = cities,
    type = types,
    beverage_count = counts,
    est = ests,
    status = status
)
}

This function, which I named scape_beverage_producer, takes the urls that were output by the scrape_url function as its input. It gets the producer names, the cities that they are in, the type of alcohol they produce, the amount of beverages they make, the year they were established, and whether they are active or closed. Finally, it creates a dataframe of all of this data.

California Data Wrangling

ca_beverages <- ca_beverages[c(-60, -80),]

I took out these two rows because they were missing data for the city column, which I need for my visualizations later.

ca_city_state_lon_lat <- ca_beverages %>%
  add_column(state = "California") %>%
  distinct(city, state, type) %>%
  mutate(city_state = paste(city, state, sep = ", ")) %>%
  mutate_geocode(city_state)
  
ca_city_count <- ca_beverages %>%
  group_by(city) %>%
  summarise(count = n())

ca_data <- ca_city_count %>%
  inner_join(ca_city_state_lon_lat) %>%
  select(-state, -city_state)
write.csv(ca_data, "ca_beverages_geo.csv")
ca_mapping_data <- read.csv("data/ca_beverages_geo.csv")

In the first code chunk, I created a dataframe called ca_city_state_lat_lon, which contains all of the states that are contained in the ca_beverages dataframe along with the type of producer in that city, the state name, its full name with the state, and its latitude and longitude data. I specifically created the city_state vector so because I used the data in that column as input for the mutate_geocode function in order to find the latitude and longitude data.

In the second chunk, I created a dataframe called ca_city_count, which contains the number of producers in each city. I did this by using grouping by city and then counting the number of types.

In the third chunk, I created the ca_data dataframe by joining the ca_city_count dataframe with the ca_city_state_lat_lon dataframe. The ca_data dataframe contains the city, the number of producers in that city, the type of producer in that city, the state name, and finally the longitude and latitude data for each city.

After all of that, I created a csv file from the ca_data dataframe and set the chunks above to eval = FALSE, which means that they will appear in the knitted file but not run. I did this because otherwise it would use ton of RAM to get the longitude and latitude data every time I knit this document. I loaded the csv file that I created and created the dataframes ca_mapping_data from it to use for geospatial mapping.
